    <!-- Slide 4: Contributions to AI and Computing -->
    <div id="slide4" class="slide">
        <div class="slide-content">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-800">The Connection to AI</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700">Almost a century after his death, George Boole's work became the bedrock of modern computing. In 1937, a young MIT graduate student named <strong>Claude Shannon</strong> wrote his master's thesis, "A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits." Shannon demonstrated that Boolean logic could be used to design and simplify complex electrical circuits.</p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mt-4">This was the pivotal moment that connected Boole's abstract mathematics to the physical world of electronics. The "true" and "false" of Boolean logic became the "on" and "off" of switches and transistors, forming the binary code (1s and 0s) that is the universal language of computers.</p>
            <div class="flex justify-center">
                <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300/a3e635/FFFFFF?text=Claude+Shannon+and+his+Thesis" alt="Claude Shannon with his thesis" class="rounded-xl shadow-lg">
            </div>
            <a href="https://www.historyofinformation.com/detail.php?id=622" target="_blank" class="nav-button bg-green-600 text-white mt-4 inline-flex">
                <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
                    <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 4a2 2 0 00-2 2v8a2 2 0 002 2h12a2 2 0 002-2V6a2 2 0 00-2-2H4zm1 5.5a.5.5 0 01.5-.5h5a.5.5 0 01.5.5v3.5a.5.5 0 01-.5.5h-5a.5.5 0 01-.5-.5v-3.5zm7 0a.5.5 0 01.5-.5h2a.5.5 0 01.5.5v3.5a.5.5 0 01-.5.5h-2a.5.5 0 01-.5-.5v-3.5z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
                </svg>
                Read Shannon's Thesis Summary
            </a>
        </div>
